@node whatis What are these DCC clients?

@{b}What is DCC?@{ub}

    DCC, short for Direct Client Connection, is a method of direct
communication between two IRC clients, without the intermediate IRC server
network. This reduces both the connection lag and the load on the IRC
servers, greatly benefiting both speed and general IRC usability.

    For these reasons, DCC is an ideal protocol for transfering files.
This is what DCC.Send and DCC.Move do.

@{b}DCC.Send@{ub}

    DCC.Send is an ircII-compatible file transfer client for the Grapevine
IRC program. It features a graphic interface for easy monitoring of the
progress of the transfer, and, if so desired, abort it, and an optimised
sending routine which makes it faster than the ircII counterpart,
especially on slow lines or in lag conditions.

@{b}DCC.Move@{ub}

    DCC.Move is a client specifically written for Grapevine, supporting
filenames with spaces in them, and transfer resume. Unlike in the past,
DCC.Move is not significanty faster than DCC.Send, since both have been
optimised for maximum performance. However, DCC.Move does use a bit less
bandwidth, which could make it more desirable on low speed connections.

@{b}DCC.Chat@{ub}

    DCC.Chat is another ircII-compatible client, this time for a
"talk"-like private chat connection. It features a fully resizable and
font sensitive interface, scroll back buffer, and clipboard support.
DCC.Chat uses the textfield.gadget by Mark Thomas.

@{b}Compatibility with TCP/IP stacks@{ub}

    While these clients are written for Commodore's AS225r2 networking
software, they will work with AmiTCP using the freely available AS225
emulation socket.library. You should already have this installed, if
Grapevine is operational. However, see @{"this AmiTCP usage note" link amitcp}.

@endnode

@node install Installing

@{b}Installation instructions@{ub}

    Installation is done by simply doubleclicking the Install icon and
following instructions. The script uses Commodore's Installer tool, which
is not included in the archive.

    To install the DCC clients by hand, simply copy the DCC.Send.AS225,
DCC.Move.AS225 and DCC.Chat.AS225 programs to the directory you specified
as the "DCC Program Path" in the Grapevine "Paths" window. Copy
textfield.gadget to SYS:Classes/Gadgets.

    You may @{"configure" link variables} certain aspects of the operation
of the programs using some environment variables.

@endnode

@node using Using DCC.Send

@{b}So how do I use DCC.Send and DCC.Move?@{ub}

    @{"Sending a file         " link send}
    @{"Receiving a file       " link get}
    @{"Aborting a transfer    " link abort}

@{b}What about DCC.Chat?@{ub}

    @{"Starting a chat        " link chat}

@endnode

@node send Sending a file

@{b}Sending a file@{ub}

    Use of DCC.Send is through the Grapevine main program.  To send a
file to a user, you would type:

    /dcc send nickname filename

    or, for DCC.Move,

    /dcc move nickname filename

    Where "nickname" is the IRC Nick of the person you wish to send the
file to, and "filename" is the full path and filename of the file you want
to send (example: Work:Utilities/Sabot). If you omit the filename portion
of the line, then DCC.Send will open a file requester so that you may
select a file you wish to send.  Selecting "Cancel" from the filerequester
will abort the file transfer.

    By specifying a directory only (ending with : or /) as the filename,
the file requester will be opened with the path set to that directory.

    If the file specified is found, DCC.Send will open a progress indicator
@{"window" link window} that tells of the current state of the transfer.

@endnode

@node get Receiving a file

@{b}Receiving a file@{ub}

    Use of DCC.Send is through the Grapevine main program.  When another
IRC user attempts to send you a file via DCC, DCC.Send will open a
requester with three options.  You may @{b}Accept@{ub} the connection,
which will start the file transfer, and place the file in the directory you
specified in Grapevine's "Path" window, you may @{b}Rename@{ub} the file,
which will open a file requester which allows you to pick a new path and
filename for the incoming program, or you may @{b}Cancel@{ub} the request,
and not accept the file.

    If you cancel a send at this point, the sender is informed of this in
an IRC notice, so that he or she may cancel the waiting send on that end.

    DCC.Move has an extra feature at this point: If the file already exists
in the destination directory, DCC.Move will ask whether you would like to
@{b}Resume@{ub} transfer or @{b}Restart@{ub} the transfer from the
beginning. It has a rudimentary file checksum, which will force it to
start from beginning if the common part of the files on both ends differs.
Being a very simple algorithm, this is not foolproof, but works most of
the time. Note that transfer resume COULD end up with a corrupted file.

    This initial requester can also be bypassed, forcing any incoming file
to be automatically accepted. See @{"configuration" link variables} for information
about this.

@endnode

@node abort Aborting a transfer

@{b}Aborting a transfer@{ub}

    To abort a transfer already in progress, simply click the close gadget
in the progress window. There may be a short delay while the client tells
the other party that you are canceling the transfer.

@endnode

@node chat Using DCC.Chat

@{b}Using DCC.Chat@{ub}

    When you want to start a chat connection with someone, simply type in
the Grapevine main window:

    /dcc chat nickname

    DCC.Chat will open its window and send a chat request to the other
party. When that request is acknowledged, it will notify about it and
enable the string gadget in which you can the type the text. Lines by you
will be prepended with a "> ", while lines by the other party will start
with his/hers nickname.

    When someone wants to chat with you, DCC.Chat will open a requester
asking whether you want to accept the chat request. If you do accept it,
the window will open and a connection will be made, otherwise DCC.Chat
will send back a message notifying the other party that you refused the
connection.

@endnode

@node window The progress window

@{b}The DCC.Send / DCC.Move window@{ub}

    When a DCC transfer begins, DCC.Send will open a small window located
near the Grapevine window in which the DCC was initiated (or the lowest
number window if you are accepting).  The DCC.Send window consists of
three parts.

    @{b}Gauge@{ub}     This is a progress gauge which graphically shows how
          much of a transfer is complete.  The percentage transfered is
          shown in the center of the gauge.

    @{b}Filename@{ub}  This field tells the name of the file being
          transferred.

    @{b}Size@{ub}      The number of bytes transfered, and the total number
          of bytes is shown here.

    @{b}Speed@{ub}     A "bytes per second" indication of the average transfer
          speed is shown in this third area.

    The title bar of the window indicates whether the transfer is incoming or
outgoing, and the nickname of the remote party.

@{b}DCC.Chat window@{ub}

    DCC.Chat window consist of a text field with a scroll gadget, and a
string gadget in which you can type text.

@endnode

@node tia Note to TIA users

@{b}Note to TIA users:@{ub}

    At the time this was written, latest TIA beta had support for DCC
using a special kludge. This is now supported in all three DCC clients.
You can enable this support with the TIADCC environment variable. This
variable is of the form "<TIA host> <low port> <high port>", for example:

    SetEnv TIADCC "extro.ucc.su.oz.au 9400 9402"

    The port numbers have to be configured the same as for TIA itself.
<TIA host> is the name of the machine you are running TIA on. Don't forget
to make a copy of this variable to ENVARC: or you will have to reset it
after every reboot.

    Configuring the UNIX side (make sure you are using TIA v1.04c or
higher) is done by adding a line with an -r option for every port assigned
for DCC to the ".tiarc" file. Continuing the example, you would add  the
following lines:

    -r:9400 9400
    -r:9401 9401
    -r:9402 9402

    On these lines, list all the ports between, and including, the <low
port> and <high port> you specified in the TIADCC variable on your Amiga.

    If you want more than 3 DCCs at once, you can increase the <high port>
and add more -r options to .tiarc.

    Port numbers can be anything from 1111 to 9999, but they have to be
sequential, and the higher they are, the more chance TIA has obtaining
them.

    (Thanks to Michael Lorant for bugging the TIA developers and me long
enough to make us implement this, and writing the first version of this
part of the document. He reports that DCC.Move does also work with TIA.
Have fun...)

@endnode

@node additional Additional Goodies

@{i}Additional Goodies@{ui}

    @{b}ProcessFile.rexx@{ub}

    This user customisable ARexx script processes files according to the
extension. For example, it shows text files, plays samples, and decompresses
LhA archives. It also handles files compressed with gzip or compress.

    If you enhance this script, please @{"send your version" link ack} to
me for inclusion on future releases.

    @{b}DCC.Redirect@{ub}

    This is a very simple program for redirecting an incoming DCC request
to another IRC client, should you for some reason need that.

    @{b}NewObtainGIRPort@{ub}

    This is a simple patch to the Intuition ObtainGIRPort() call, fixing a
deadlock situation between BOOPSI gadgets such as textfield.gadget used in
DCC.Chat, and programs such as Magic Menu and CycleToMenu.

@endnode

@node danimalize Automatic incoming file accept

@{i}Danimalize!@{ui}

    If you would like to automatically accept any DCC request sent to
you, simply set the environment variable DANIMALIZE (example: "SetEnv
DANIMALIZE 1").  This will mean that whenever anyone else on IRC tries
to send you a file, it will skip the Accept/Rename/Cancel requester, and
just accept the transfer. Similarly, this will open Chat automatically
and force resume mode in DCC.Move. Not to worry though, because of the
checksum algorithm, DCC.Move is likely to detect if the file is not really
resumable, in which case it will simply start from the beginning.

    This feature may be replaced with a pattern list of trusted people's
nicknames, for which the files are accepted, if there is need for this.

@endnode

@node process Incoming file processing

@{b}File processing@{ub}

    DCC.Send can execute a program after receiving a file. To use this
feature, set ENV:PROCESSDCC to the name of the command. In this command,
the first %s will be replaced with the filename (full path included), and
the second (optional) with the Grapevine public screen name. For example,
to use the provided example script @{"ProcessFile.rexx" link additional}, copy this script to
REXX: and give the command

    SetEnv PROCESSDCC SYS:RexxC/RX REXX:ProcessFile.rexx "%s" "%s"

in the shell. Naturally you can replace this with whatever you want, for
example a command to DOpus.. If you don't want to use this feature, just
leave the variable unset. And again, don't forget to copy the variable
to ENVARC: if you want it to stay around after a reboot.

    It is recommended that you use full paths to all commands used in the
file processing, because Grapevine might not provide DCC.Send with a
complete search path if it has been started from the Workbench or by some
utility like ToolManager.

@endnode

@node variables Enviroment variables used in DCC.Send

@{b}Environment variables used@{ub}

    DCC.Send and DCC.Move can be configured with a couple of environment
variables. Here is a list:

    @{"HOSTNAME" link amitcp}    If normal hostname lookup fails, it will check this
                variable instead. If used, it needs to have the @{i}full domain
                name.@{ui} See @{"use with AmiTCP" link amitcp}.

    @{"TIADCC" link tia}     Parameters for port selection for TIA use.

    @{"DANIMALIZE" link danimalize} Forces DCC.Send to automatically accept any
                incoming file.

    @{"PROCESSDCC" link process} Command to execute after a successful receive.

@endnode

@node amitcp Using DCC.Send with AmiTCP

    AmiTCP socket.library has a problem with gethostname() function, used
to get the host name of your system. Especially in the case of dynamic IP
systems, there are multitudes of errors in this respect. For this reason,
DCC.Send reads the host name from the HOSTNAME environment variable if it
is unable to resolve the host name with gethostname(). If you have
problems with this, set ENV:HOSTNAME to your @{b}full host name@{ub},
including domain.

@endnode

@node history Changes in DCC.Send

@{b}What has happened to DCC.Send?@{ub}

@{i}1.12@{ui}

    Slightly more forgiving.. ;)
    Included a simple DCC.Chat client.

@{i}1.10@{ui}

    Just how many people can fuck a simple installation up, and come
    blaming me? Well, one error message added for those AmiTCP users who
    fail to set ENV:HOSTNAME.

@{i}1.9@{ui}

    Fixed a memory corruption problem if started with a very long file
    name (>127 characters).. Should make it more bomb-proof.
    Tested under very low memory conditions, couldn't make it crash.

@{i}1.8@{ui}

    Internal version

@{i}1.7@{ui}

    Well, the change made it even more confusing. Made another change.

@{i}1.6@{ui}

    Oops, slight bug in status display when ending a send..

@{i}1.5@{ui}

    Argh.. Was looking for files in the wrong place, because I had
    forgotten put back the change first done in 0.34.. Sorry about that.
    Updates gauge now only once per second instead of after every packet.
    This makes it LOTS faster on high speed links like a good Ethernet.

@{i}1.4@{ui}

    Internal version.

@{i}1.3@{ui}

    Now *really* works on OS 2.0.
    A silly change to help in testing: will accept an address as a host name
    as well as an IP integer, and outputs the completion message to stdout
    if not started by Grapevine.

@{i}1.2@{ui}

    *sigh*.. lost the source, rewrote it back from v 0.31... I hope I
    didn't miss anything. If it wasn't for Scott Ellis, who had the 0.31
    source, you wouldn't see this version at all. Keep backups, guys.

    Changed so that V39 (OS 3.0) is no longer required, will work on V37
    (OS 2.0) upwards.
    Made the window a bit wider, with large files the size was getting
    clipped.
    Added ability to run a program to do processing on the file after a
    successful receive.

@{i}1.1@{ui}

    Oops. Wasn't freeing all socket resources properly if started from the
    CLI without the necessary arguments.

@{i}1.0@{ui}

    We're not beta anymore!
    Raised disk buffers to 32 KB.. Should be enough even for the fastest
    connection. This used to be 8 KB, which meant constant disk access on
    a fast Ethernet.
    Better documentation for using DCC.Send with TIA.

@{i}0.x@{ui}

    Beta versions...

@endnode
